[normal]Clearly, whereas BBC is dominant in TV news viewing, it is only average when
[normal] 
[normal]judged by TV news viewers in respect of these fundamental criteria of news
[normal] 
[normal]reportage.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BBCʼs (Comparative) Presence in Radio News
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BBC UK-wid
[normal]e radio stations include the top three radio stations used nowadays for
[normal] 
[normal]news, these being Radio 4 (26%), Radio 2 (25%) and Radio 1 (19%) (A5 pp. 32-33
[normal] 
[normal]and Chart 3.4.4).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It may be observed of Chart 
[normal]3.4.4 that 9 of the 15 featured radio stations are BBC
[normal] 
[normal]stations and that in aggregate BBC UK-wide stations account for two-thirds of those
[normal] 
[normal]who use radio for news.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BBCʼs (Comparative) Presence in Online News
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Of the 41% of UK adults who say they use the in
[normal]ternet for news, the main source
[normal] 
[normal]used is the BBC website or a BBC app (57%) (A4 4.39 and Fig. 10). Tying for
[normal] 
[normal]second place are Facebook and Google (19% each), with Sky News website or app
[normal] 
[normal]coming third (17%).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]According to UKOM/Nielsen in December 2011 there
[normal] were then nine online news
[normal] 
[normal]brands reaching over 2 million people each month and of these the BBC had the
[normal] 
[normal]highest reach, with 11 million people. DMGT and Yahoo were next, with 6.6 and 4.1
[normal] 
[normal]million respectively (A4 4.99 and Fig. 26). BSkyB came in with 1.3 m
[normal]illion.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Even when looking at the BBCʼs presence online in general terms, i.e. not restricted
[normal] 
[normal]to news, it is number five top site in the UK, first and second being google.co.uk and
[normal] 
[normal]google.com, followed by facebook.com and youtube.com (Alexa)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Users of news
[normal] websites rated the broadcasters BBC and Sky fairly evenly across
[normal] 
[normal]attributes.
